{"title_page": "Marie Warder", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use South African English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Marie Warder\n| birth_name  = Marie Van Zyl<br/>''alt'' Marie Van Zijl\n| image = Marie Warder 2.jpg\n| alt         = Photo of Marie Warder\n| caption     = Marie Warder\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|df=yes|1927|4|30}}\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|df=yes|2014|10|20|1927|4|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Ficksburg]], South Africa\n|death_place = [[Tsawwassen, British Columbia|Tsawwassen]], [[British Columbia]]\n| nationality = South African, Canadian\n| known_for   = [[Hemochromatosis]] activism\n| occupation  = [[Journalist]] and [[author]]\n}}\n\n'''Marie Warder''' (born Marie van Zyl, 30 April 1927 \u2013 20 October 2014) was a journalist, novelist and activist best known for her activities raising awareness about [[hemochromatosis]].<ref>Ferguson, Dan. \"A writer's return.\" ''Surrey Leader'' [Surrey, British Columbia] 25 May 2008: 9. ''Infotrac Newsstand''. GALE|A227576707. Retrieved 21 November 2012. Also published in ''South Delta Leader'' [Delta, British Columbia]. (13 June 2008)</ref>  Warder founded the Hemochromatosis Society of South Africa,<ref name=HSSA>{{cite web |url=http://www.haemochromatosisza.org/marie-warder-visit.html |title=Marie Warder Visits South Africa |publisher=Haemochromatosis Society of South Africa |accessdate=21 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110416065446/http://www.haemochromatosisza.org/marie-warder-visit.html |archive-date=16 April 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the [[Canadian Hemochromatosis Society]] (CHS),<ref name=CHS>{{cite web|url=http://www.toomuchiron.ca/about/history.php |title=History |publisher=Canadian Hemochromatosis Society |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826175138/http://www.toomuchiron.ca/about/history.php |archivedate=26 August 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|VFGXxS9E8xM}}</ref> and was founder and long-time president of the International Association of Hemochromatosis Societies (IAHS), writing the detailing leaflets  for them all, which  meant that, at that stage, every publication of the Canadian Hemochromatosis Society carried the footnote: \"Produced for the International Association of Haemochromatosis Societies.\"\n\nAny emerging or fledgling hemochromatosis society in other parts of the world was free to use her material, with due acknowledgement to the IAHS. Later, Guy Fernau, founder of the Haemochromatosis Society in the United Kingdom, related how, before his own material could be prepared, he only needed to scan the Canadian pamphlet and change the spelling.\n\n== Biography ==\n\nWarder was born Marie van Zyl in [[Ficksburg]], South Africa in 1927.  She married Tom Warder when she was 19 and he 21, upon his return from active service in [[World War II]], and later moved with him to Canada.  Tom was diagnosed with hemochromatosis in 1975, and their daughter was diagnosed with the same disorder in 1979. These two events spurred Warder to become an activist, raising awareness of this disorder within the medical community and the general public.\n\n=== Journalism career ===\nWarder's first editor was once heard to say that his young prot\u00e9g\u00e9e must have been  born with printer's ink in her veins for her journalistic \"career\" began at the age of nine when she won first prize in a province-wide essay competition launched by the administrator of what was then known as \"the Orange Free State\" in South Africa. The subject she  chose was \"The Natural Order of Lepidoptera\" and the prize was a Queen Victoria silver penny of the kind given to deserving poor people as  part of a religious ceremony held on the Thursday before Easter.\n\nIn February 1939, having already written a play, ''The Secret of the Kennels'' for the [[SABC]] children's program ''Young Ideas'' the previous year, Warder began writing stories for local newspapers, selling her first story to the ''[[Cape Argus]]'' at age 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abcbookworld.com/view_author.php?id=4441|title=WARDER, Marie|publisher=ABC Bookworld|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2010}} In 1944, she had had two stories published in the British magazine ''[[Everybody's Weekly|Everybody's]]'' and later wrote for several South African periodicals.\n\nBy 17, she was also the chief reporter for the [[Germiston]] ''Advocate''. In this role, Warder was reportedly the youngest chief reporter in the world.<ref>''The Ficksburg News, 1946''</ref>  Warder had the chance to interview, among others, [[Pat Boone]],<ref>\"My shortest interview ever\", Amalgamated Press (SA) Ltd. April  1960, on different dates, in other branches in the chain</ref> Field Marshal [[Jan Christiaan Smuts]] and [[Frances Steloff]], founder of New York's [[Gotham Book Mart]] in 1920.<ref>Germiston Advocate in 1944</ref>\n\nWarder's journalism career is most noted for her numerous pamphlets and articles on the subject of hemochromatosis.\n\n=== Writing career ===\nWhile still living in South Africa, Warder took to writing fiction. She is the author of twenty-four novels,<ref>\n{{cite news\n  |url=http://archive.delta-optimist.com/issues06/024206/community/024206co5.html\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709011528/http://archive.delta-optimist.com/issues06/024206/community/024206co5.html\n  |archivedate=9 July 2011\n  |title=Author adds another chapter in Stories from South Africa\n  |last=Willis\n  |first=Dave\n  |date=2006-02-25\n  |work=Delta Optimist\n  |quote=In addition to a series of fiction novels, called Stories from South Africa, Warder has written ''The Bronze Killer'', a non-fiction book on hemochromatosis.\n  |accessdate=10 August 2010\n\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n  |url=http://www.langleyadvance.com/health/Tsawwassen+author+release+pair+novels+books/2827167/story.html\n  |title=Tsawwassen author to release pair of her novels as e-books\n  |date=15 April 2009\n  |work=Langley Advance\n  |quote=...novels, Samaritan of the Sahara and The Yardstick, are part of her Stories from South Africa series.\n  |accessdate=10 August 2010\n}}{{dead link|date=November 2012}}</ref> written in English and [[Afrikaans language|Afrikaans]];<ref name=WorldCat>\n{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.worldcat.org/wcidentities/lccn-n91-17991\n  |title=Warder, Marie\n  |work=[[WorldCat]]\n}}</ref>  three of which were used for some years as required reading in South African schools.{{Ref|*|*}} Many of her stories take place in and around newspaper offices.\n\nWarder\u2019s biography is included in the Archives of the National Council of Women among \"Notable Women of Johannesburg\".<ref>Notification 1963</ref>\n\nLate in 2003, Warder returned to novel writing. ''Storm Water'' and ''With no remorse\u2026'' were released simultaneously less than a year later. In late 2010, Warder was working on her 23rd book: an updated version of ''Penny of the Morning Star'', a novel she had originally written in South Africa in the 1960s as a part of a training course in [[English as a second language]].<ref name=DeltaOptimistNov2010>{{cite news\n |url          = http://www.delta-optimist.com/health/Warder+just+stop+writing/3892249/story.html\n |title        = Warder just can't stop writing\n |work         = Delta Optimist\n |date         = 27 November 2010\n |accessdate   = 28 November 2010\n |last         = Willis\n |first        = Dave\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110928092712/http://www.delta-optimist.com/health/Warder+just+stop+writing/3892249/story.html#\n |archive-date = 28 September 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref>  Her latest book, ''April in Portugal'', was released late in May 2011, and she currently writes a series of \"Little Kindle Tales for Little People.\"\n\n=== Hemochromatosis activism ===\n[[File:Tom Warder (Medium) (Medium) (2) (Large) (Large) (Large).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Tom Warder, Marie's husband, whose fight with [[hemochromatosis]] was the catalyst for her crusade against this disorder.]]\n\nIn 1975, Warder's husband, Tom, who had been seriously ill for eight years, was finally diagnosed with hemochromatosis at the age of 50,<ref>\"Unusual bronze diabetes deadly blood disorder\". ''The Ottawa Citizen'' [Ottawa, Ont] 14 Aug 1987: C5.</ref> and died in 1992.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  |url=http://thisisnotaperfectworld.blogspot.com/2010/06/frederick-abinger-tom-warder.html\n  |title=Frederick Abinger (Tom) Warder - the world\u2019s \"most famous Hemochromatosis patient.\"\n  |last=Warder|first=Marie\n  |date=2010-06-12\n  |accessdate=8 August 2010\n}}</ref> In 1979 their daughter, then 32, was also diagnosed with hemochromatosis. Warder concluded that the disorder was hereditary and that much of what she had been told about it was incorrect: women could indeed develop hemochromatosis, and it was not only a disorder of middle-age. Warder made it her mission to make the world aware of this disorder, including an interview with Ida Clarkson on [[CHEK]] television.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VFGXxS9E8xM\n  |title=Ida Clarkson - CHEK television\n}}</ref>  For more than 28 years after that, except for a series of travel articles, Warder devoted her literary efforts to works about hemochromatosis.  During this time she wrote ''The Bronze Killer'',<ref>\n{{cite book\n  |title = The Bronze Killer : the Story of a Family's Fight Against a Very Common Enemy, Hemochromatosis\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Maple Lane Publishing\n  |year=2000\n  |isbn=978-0-9687358-0-0\n}}</ref><ref>Marilyn Dunlop. \"When she was 19, Marie Warder fell deeply in\". ''Toronto Star'' [Toronto, Ont]. 5 June 1989: C1.</ref> the first devoted entirely to the subject of the genetic disorder [[hemochromatosis]].  The term \"Bronze Killer\" has been used, among others, in the ''[[Toronto Star]]'',<ref>''The Toronto Star'' November 1987</ref> in British newspapers, in the magazine supplement of the ''Johannesburg Sunday Express''<ref>''The Johannesburg Sunday express'', in 1987</ref> and in a Quebec French issue of the ''[[Reader's Digest]]'', where it is called \"''La tueuse au masque du bronze''\".<ref name=\"Selection 1995\"/> Hemochromatosis was referred to as \"the bronze killer\" in an editorial by [[Clement Finch]], Professor of Medicine Emeritus of the [[University of Washington]], in the ''[[Western Journal of Medicine]]'', September 1990.<ref name=Finch>\n{{cite journal\n  |title=Hemochromatosis--treatment is easy, diagnosis hard\n  |journal=Western Journal of Medicine\n  |date=September 1990|volume=153|issue=3\n  |last=Finch|first=Clement|pmc=1002547|pmid=2219902\n  |pages=323\u20135\n}}</ref>\n\nWarder went on to found hemochromatosis societies in South Africa and Canada.<ref name=\"HSSA\" /><ref name=CHS/>\n\nWarder has also published more than 300 articles on the subject of hemochromatosis, as well as patient literature for individuals, hospitals and other medical facilities. Her newsletters and brochures have gone out to more than 16 countries.<ref name=CHS/>\n\n=== Other activities ===\nIn addition to her activities as a writer and activist, Warder has been an educator, founding and serving as the first principal of Windsor House Academy, a \"dual-medium\" school in [[Kempton Park, Gauteng|Kempton Park]], South Africa; and a musician, playing piano and [[clavioline]] with her husband's band.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.vimeo.com/9847491\n  |title=Tom Warder's band\n  |work=Vimeo.com\n}}</ref> and, late in life, a lay chaplain at the Delta Hospital in [[Ladner, British Columbia]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n  |title=Author steps back in time to South Africa\n  |quote=Today, Marie Warder lives in [[Tsawwassen, British Columbia]], where for more than seven years, between 1995 and 2002, she was well-known as a chaplain at the Delta Hospital\n  |first=Jan|last=Westell\n  |work=Delta Optimist\n  |date= 1 January 2003\n}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n=== Fiction ===\n;English\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Storm Water\n  |series=Stories from South Africa Series\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Maple Lane Publishing\n  |year=2003\n  |isbn=978-0-921966-05-0\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=With No Remorse\n  |series=Stories from South Africa Series\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Dromedaris Books\n  |year=2003\n  |isbn=978-0-921966-03-6\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=When You Know -- that You Know, that You Know!\n  |volume=3\n  |series=Stories from South Africa\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Maple Lane Publishing\n  |year=2004\n  |isbn=978-0-921966-09-8\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Tarnished Idols\n  |series=Stories from South Africa\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Dromedaris Books\n  |year=2004\n  |isbn=978-0-921966-07-4\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Dominic Verwey Samaritan of the Sahara\n  |series=Stories from South Africa\n  |volume=5\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Booksurge Llc\n  |year=2006\n  |isbn=978-0-9733625-0-3\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=The Yardstick\n  |series=Stories from South Africa Series\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Booksurge Llc\n  |year=2007\n  |isbn=978-0-9733625-1-0\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Penny of the Morning Star: The Story of a Girl Reporter in the Nineteen Forties\n  |series=Stories from South Africa\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Maple Lane Publishing\n  |year=2010\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=April in Portugal\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Dromedaris Books|year=2011\n  |isbn=978-0-9733625-4-1\n}}\n; Afrikaans\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Klei-Voete\n  |trans-title=Feet of Clay\n  |last=Warder|first=Marie\n  |publisher=Die Goeie Hoop Uitgewers\n  |year=1953\n  |asin=B0040MIFXS\n}}\n* {{cite book \n  |title=Samaritaan van die Sahara\n  |trans-title=Samaritan of the Sahara\n  |publisher=Dagbreek-Boekkring\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |location=Johannesburg\n  |year=1954\n  |oclc=37484386\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Niemand so Blind\n  |trans-title=None So Blind\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Dagbreek-Boekkring\n  |location=Johannesburg\n  |year=1959\n  |oclc=36230980\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Deur sonskyn en skaduwee\n  |trans-title=Through Sunshine and Shadow\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Dagbreek-Boekkring\n  |location=Johannesburg\n  |year=1961\n  |oclc=504531563\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Die maatstok\n  |trans-title=The Dipstick\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |oclc=14643120\n  |publisher=Dagbreek-Boekkring\n  |location=Johannesburg\n  |year=1963\n}}\n\n=== Nonfiction ===\n* {{cite book\n  |title = The Bronze Killer: The Story of a Family's Fight Against a Very Common Enemy - Hemochromatosis\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher = Imperani Publishers Publishers\n  |year=1989\n  |isbn=0-88925-885-6\n}} (Updated in 2000 as ''The Bronze Killer: New Edition'' (Dromedaris Books, {{ISBN|9780968735800}}) including \"Iron: The Other Side of the Story\", a layman's guide to hemochromatosis)\n\n== Recognition ==\n{{multiple image|align=right\n|image1=Ottawa1991.jpg|width1=215|caption1=Warder with the Canada Volunteer Medal of Honour\n|image2=|width2=138|caption2=Warder's Medal of Honour\n}}\n\nFor her efforts in founding the CHS, Warder was presented with a certificate of appreciation on 11 April 1988 by Mayor G.J. Blair, of Richmond, British Columbia \"in recognition of her contribution to voluntary service\" in that city, one year after he had been the first Mayor in Canada to proclaim an annual week of awareness for Hemochromatosis. During the first Awareness Week, 523 new cases of hemochromatosis were diagnosed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdnhemochromatosis.ca/about/history.php |title=History |publisher=Canadian Hemochromatosis Society |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706172308/http://www.cdnhemochromatosis.ca/about/history.php |archivedate=6 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she was presented with a Lifetime Achievement Award at the International Bio-Iron Conference held in Vancouver, \"honoring her lifelong involvement and dedication to the awareness of Hemochromatosis around the world.\"<ref>{{cite news\n |url          = http://www.delta-optimist.com/health/Lifetime+award+author/4886690/story.html\n |title        = Lifetime award for author\n |work         = The Delta Optimist\n |date         = 3 June 2011\n |author       = Staff\n |access-date  = 3 June 2011\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110826052836/http://www.delta-optimist.com/health/Lifetime+award+author/4886690/story.html#\n |archive-date = 26 August 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref>   Some years ago, the Minister of Health for Canada declared May each year to be a month of National Awareness for the disorder and it is now also observed by organizations in other countries for instance the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/ahc-asc/minist/messages/_2009/2009_05_26-eng.php |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706182051/http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/ahc-asc/minist/messages/_2009/2009_05_26-eng.php |archivedate=6 July 2011 |title=Message from Leona Aglukkaq, Minister of Health: Hemochromatosis Month \u2013 May 2009 |accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref><ref>http://www.hemochromatosiscny.org/</ref>{{Relevance inline|date=November 2012}}\n\nWarder was awarded the Canada Volunteer Award in 1991 by the [[Health and Welfare Canada]] for her work and advocacy of raising awareness of hemochromatosis.<ref name=\"Selection 1995\">\n{{cite journal\n | title       = La tueuse au masque du bronze\n | journal     = Selection\n | location    = Quebec\n | date        = November 1995\n |trans-title=The Bronze Killer\n}}</ref><ref>Anderson, Donna. \"Hard-working volunteers honored with national award\". ''The Vancouver Sun'' [Vancouver, B.C] 5 July 1991: C8. Quote: \" Bea Leinback, Marie Warder and Joanna Tudan-Sainberg were among 25 people across the country who received this year's Canada Volunteer Award during a ceremony in Ottawa last week. And in keeping with the selfless character of the volunteer, they say their biggest joy was the national recognition their organizations were accorded. The award was established by Health and Welfare Canada to acknowledge the efforts of volunteers to improve the health and social well-being of their fellow Canadians.\"</ref><ref>''Delta Optimist'' (June 1991)</ref>{{Ref|***|***}}\n\n== Death ==\nWarder died on 20 October 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marie Warder Obituary|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/vancouversun/obituary.aspx?pid=173174075|accessdate=8 June 2015|publisher=Vancouver Sun|date=15 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Note|*|*}}''Storm Water'' and ''Samaritaan van die Sahara'' in [[Afrikaans language|Afrikaans]] and ''Penny of the Morning Star'' in English. The last was commissioned for use by [[English as a second language|ESL]] students, and thus contained an English/Afrikaans glossary as well as comprehension questions. An updated version for general reading, without the English/Afrikaans glossary and comprehension questions, was issued in time for Christmas 2010.<ref name=DeltaOptimistNov2010/>\n\n{{Note|**|**}}''Hart Sonder Liefde'' and ''Penny of the Morning Star - the story of a girl reporter''\n\n{{Note|***|***}}Text of Certificate: \"Through Marie Warder\u2019s research and most noted book, ''The Bronze Killer'', she has educated doctors and the general public about the disorder. As a result, hemochromatosis is now recognized as Canada\u2019s most common genetic disorder, and routine blood tests for the disorder may soon become standard diagnostic procedure.\"\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Warder, Marie}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ficksburg]]\n[[Category:South African non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:South African women novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use South African English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Marie Warder\n| birth_name  = Marie Van Zyl<br/>''alt'' Marie Van Zijl\n| image = Marie Warder 2.jpg\n| alt         = Photo of Marie Warder\n| caption     = Marie Warder\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|df=yes|1927|4|30}}\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|df=yes|2014|10|20|1927|4|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Ficksburg]], South Africa\n|death_place = [[Tsawwassen]], [[British Columbia]]\n| nationality = South African, Canadian\n| known_for   = [[Hemochromatosis]] activism\n| occupation  = [[Journalist]] and [[author]]\n}}\n\n'''Marie Warder''' (born Marie van Zyl, 30 April 1927 \u2013 20 October 2014) was a journalist, novelist and activist best known for her activities raising awareness about [[hemochromatosis]].<ref>Ferguson, Dan. \"A writer's return.\" ''Surrey Leader'' [Surrey, British Columbia] 25 May 2008: 9. ''Infotrac Newsstand''. GALE|A227576707. Retrieved 21 November 2012. Also published in ''South Delta Leader'' [Delta, British Columbia]. (13 June 2008)</ref>  Warder founded the Hemochromatosis Society of South Africa,<ref name=HSSA>{{cite web |url=http://www.haemochromatosisza.org/marie-warder-visit.html |title=Marie Warder Visits South Africa |publisher=Haemochromatosis Society of South Africa |accessdate=21 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110416065446/http://www.haemochromatosisza.org/marie-warder-visit.html |archive-date=16 April 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the [[Canadian Hemochromatosis Society]] (CHS),<ref name=CHS>{{cite web|url=http://www.toomuchiron.ca/about/history.php |title=History |publisher=Canadian Hemochromatosis Society |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826175138/http://www.toomuchiron.ca/about/history.php |archivedate=26 August 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|VFGXxS9E8xM}}</ref> and was founder and long-time president of the International Association of Hemochromatosis Societies (IAHS), writing the detailing leaflets  for them all, which  meant that, at that stage, every publication of the Canadian Hemochromatosis Society carried the footnote: \"Produced for the International Association of Haemochromatosis Societies.\"\n\nAny emerging or fledgling hemochromatosis society in other parts of the world was free to use her material, with due acknowledgement to the IAHS. Later, Guy Fernau, founder of the Haemochromatosis Society in the United Kingdom, related how, before his own material could be prepared, he only needed to scan the Canadian pamphlet and change the spelling.\n\n== Biography ==\n\nWarder was born Marie van Zyl in [[Ficksburg]], South Africa in 1927.  She married Tom Warder when she was 19 and he 21, upon his return from active service in [[World War II]], and later moved with him to Canada.  Tom was diagnosed with hemochromatosis in 1975, and their daughter was diagnosed with the same disorder in 1979. These two events spurred Warder to become an activist, raising awareness of this disorder within the medical community and the general public.\n\n=== Journalism career ===\nWarder's first editor was once heard to say that his young prot\u00e9g\u00e9e must have been  born with printer's ink in her veins for her journalistic \"career\" began at the age of nine when she won first prize in a province-wide essay competition launched by the administrator of what was then known as \"the Orange Free State\" in South Africa. The subject she  chose was \"The Natural Order of Lepidoptera\" and the prize was a Queen Victoria silver penny of the kind given to deserving poor people as  part of a religious ceremony held on the Thursday before Easter.\n\nIn February 1939, having already written a play, ''The Secret of the Kennels'' for the [[SABC]] children's program ''Young Ideas'' the previous year, Warder began writing stories for local newspapers, selling her first story to the ''[[Cape Argus]]'' at age 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abcbookworld.com/view_author.php?id=4441|title=WARDER, Marie|publisher=ABC Bookworld|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2010}} In 1944, she had had two stories published in the British magazine ''[[Everybody's Weekly|Everybody's]]'' and later wrote for several South African periodicals.\n\nBy 17, she was also the chief reporter for the [[Germiston]] ''Advocate''. In this role, Warder was reportedly the youngest chief reporter in the world.<ref>''The Ficksburg News, 1946''</ref>  Warder had the chance to interview, among others, [[Pat Boone]],<ref>\"My shortest interview ever\", Amalgamated Press (SA) Ltd. April  1960, on different dates, in other branches in the chain</ref> Field Marshal [[Jan Christiaan Smuts]] and [[Frances Steloff]], founder of New York's [[Gotham Book Mart]] in 1920.<ref>Germiston Advocate in 1944</ref>\n\nWarder's journalism career is most noted for her numerous pamphlets and articles on the subject of hemochromatosis.\n\n=== Writing career ===\nWhile still living in South Africa, Warder took to writing fiction. She is the author of twenty-four novels,<ref>\n{{cite news\n  |url=http://archive.delta-optimist.com/issues06/024206/community/024206co5.html\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709011528/http://archive.delta-optimist.com/issues06/024206/community/024206co5.html\n  |archivedate=9 July 2011\n  |title=Author adds another chapter in Stories from South Africa\n  |last=Willis\n  |first=Dave\n  |date=2006-02-25\n  |work=Delta Optimist\n  |quote=In addition to a series of fiction novels, called Stories from South Africa, Warder has written ''The Bronze Killer'', a non-fiction book on hemochromatosis.\n  |accessdate=10 August 2010\n\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n  |url=http://www.langleyadvance.com/health/Tsawwassen+author+release+pair+novels+books/2827167/story.html\n  |title=Tsawwassen author to release pair of her novels as e-books\n  |date=15 April 2009\n  |work=Langley Advance\n  |quote=...novels, Samaritan of the Sahara and The Yardstick, are part of her Stories from South Africa series.\n  |accessdate=10 August 2010\n}}{{dead link|date=November 2012}}</ref> written in English and [[Afrikaans language|Afrikaans]];<ref name=WorldCat>\n{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.worldcat.org/wcidentities/lccn-n91-17991\n  |title=Warder, Marie\n  |work=[[WorldCat]]\n}}</ref>  three of which were used for some years as required reading in South African schools.{{Ref|*|*}} Many of her stories take place in and around newspaper offices.\n\nWarder\u2019s biography is included in the Archives of the National Council of Women among \"Notable Women of Johannesburg\".<ref>Notification 1963</ref>\n\nLate in 2003, Warder returned to novel writing. ''Storm Water'' and ''With no remorse\u2026'' were released simultaneously less than a year later. In late 2010, Warder was working on her 23rd book: an updated version of ''Penny of the Morning Star'', a novel she had originally written in South Africa in the 1960s as a part of a training course in [[English as a second language]].<ref name=DeltaOptimistNov2010>{{cite news\n |url          = http://www.delta-optimist.com/health/Warder+just+stop+writing/3892249/story.html\n |title        = Warder just can't stop writing\n |work         = Delta Optimist\n |date         = 27 November 2010\n |accessdate   = 28 November 2010\n |last         = Willis\n |first        = Dave\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110928092712/http://www.delta-optimist.com/health/Warder+just+stop+writing/3892249/story.html#\n |archive-date = 28 September 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref>  Her latest book, ''April in Portugal'', was released late in May 2011, and she currently writes a series of \"Little Kindle Tales for Little People.\"\n\n=== Hemochromatosis activism ===\n[[File:Tom Warder (Medium) (Medium) (2) (Large) (Large) (Large).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Tom Warder, Marie's husband, whose fight with [[hemochromatosis]] was the catalyst for her crusade against this disorder.]]\n\nIn 1975, Warder's husband, Tom, who had been seriously ill for eight years, was finally diagnosed with hemochromatosis at the age of 50,<ref>\"Unusual bronze diabetes deadly blood disorder\". ''The Ottawa Citizen'' [Ottawa, Ont] 14 Aug 1987: C5.</ref> and died in 1992.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  |url=http://thisisnotaperfectworld.blogspot.com/2010/06/frederick-abinger-tom-warder.html\n  |title=Frederick Abinger (Tom) Warder - the world\u2019s \"most famous Hemochromatosis patient.\"\n  |last=Warder|first=Marie\n  |date=2010-06-12\n  |accessdate=8 August 2010\n}}</ref> In 1979 their daughter, then 32, was also diagnosed with hemochromatosis. Warder concluded that the disorder was hereditary and that much of what she had been told about it was incorrect: women could indeed develop hemochromatosis, and it was not only a disorder of middle-age. Warder made it her mission to make the world aware of this disorder, including an interview with Ida Clarkson on [[CHEK]] television.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VFGXxS9E8xM\n  |title=Ida Clarkson - CHEK television\n}}</ref>  For more than 28 years after that, except for a series of travel articles, Warder devoted her literary efforts to works about hemochromatosis.  During this time she wrote ''The Bronze Killer'',<ref>\n{{cite book\n  |title = The Bronze Killer : the Story of a Family's Fight Against a Very Common Enemy, Hemochromatosis\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Maple Lane Publishing\n  |year=2000\n  |isbn=978-0-9687358-0-0\n}}</ref><ref>Marilyn Dunlop. \"When she was 19, Marie Warder fell deeply in\". ''Toronto Star'' [Toronto, Ont]. 5 June 1989: C1.</ref> the first devoted entirely to the subject of the genetic disorder [[hemochromatosis]].  The term \"Bronze Killer\" has been used, among others, in the ''[[Toronto Star]]'',<ref>''The Toronto Star'' November 1987</ref> in British newspapers, in the magazine supplement of the ''Johannesburg Sunday Express''<ref>''The Johannesburg Sunday express'', in 1987</ref> and in a Quebec French issue of the ''[[Reader's Digest]]'', where it is called \"''La tueuse au masque du bronze''\".<ref name=\"Selection 1995\"/> Hemochromatosis was referred to as \"the bronze killer\" in an editorial by [[Clement Finch]], Professor of Medicine Emeritus of the [[University of Washington]], in the ''[[Western Journal of Medicine]]'', September 1990.<ref name=Finch>\n{{cite journal\n  |title=Hemochromatosis--treatment is easy, diagnosis hard\n  |journal=Western Journal of Medicine\n  |date=September 1990|volume=153|issue=3\n  |last=Finch|first=Clement|pmc=1002547|pmid=2219902\n  |pages=323\u20135\n}}</ref>\n\nWarder went on to found hemochromatosis societies in South Africa and Canada.<ref name=\"HSSA\" /><ref name=CHS/>\n\nWarder has also published more than 300 articles on the subject of hemochromatosis, as well as patient literature for individuals, hospitals and other medical facilities. Her newsletters and brochures have gone out to more than 16 countries.<ref name=CHS/>\n\n=== Other activities ===\nIn addition to her activities as a writer and activist, Warder has been an educator, founding and serving as the first principal of Windsor House Academy, a \"dual-medium\" school in [[Kempton Park, Gauteng|Kempton Park]], South Africa; and a musician, playing piano and [[clavioline]] with her husband's band.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.vimeo.com/9847491\n  |title=Tom Warder's band\n  |work=Vimeo.com\n}}</ref> and, late in life, a lay chaplain at the Delta Hospital in [[Ladner, British Columbia]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n  |title=Author steps back in time to South Africa\n  |quote=Today, Marie Warder lives in [[Tsawwassen, British Columbia]], where for more than seven years, between 1995 and 2002, she was well-known as a chaplain at the Delta Hospital\n  |first=Jan|last=Westell\n  |work=Delta Optimist\n  |date= 1 January 2003\n}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n=== Fiction ===\n;English\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Storm Water\n  |series=Stories from South Africa Series\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Maple Lane Publishing\n  |year=2003\n  |isbn=978-0-921966-05-0\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=With No Remorse\n  |series=Stories from South Africa Series\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Dromedaris Books\n  |year=2003\n  |isbn=978-0-921966-03-6\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=When You Know -- that You Know, that You Know!\n  |volume=3\n  |series=Stories from South Africa\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Maple Lane Publishing\n  |year=2004\n  |isbn=978-0-921966-09-8\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Tarnished Idols\n  |series=Stories from South Africa\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Dromedaris Books\n  |year=2004\n  |isbn=978-0-921966-07-4\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Dominic Verwey Samaritan of the Sahara\n  |series=Stories from South Africa\n  |volume=5\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Booksurge Llc\n  |year=2006\n  |isbn=978-0-9733625-0-3\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=The Yardstick\n  |series=Stories from South Africa Series\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Booksurge Llc\n  |year=2007\n  |isbn=978-0-9733625-1-0\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Penny of the Morning Star: The Story of a Girl Reporter in the Nineteen Forties\n  |series=Stories from South Africa\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Maple Lane Publishing\n  |year=2010\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=April in Portugal\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Dromedaris Books|year=2011\n  |isbn=978-0-9733625-4-1\n}}\n; Afrikaans\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Klei-Voete\n  |trans-title=Feet of Clay\n  |last=Warder|first=Marie\n  |publisher=Die Goeie Hoop Uitgewers\n  |year=1953\n  |asin=B0040MIFXS\n}}\n* {{cite book \n  |title=Samaritaan van die Sahara\n  |trans-title=Samaritan of the Sahara\n  |publisher=Dagbreek-Boekkring\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |location=Johannesburg\n  |year=1954\n  |oclc=37484386\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Niemand so Blind\n  |trans-title=None So Blind\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Dagbreek-Boekkring\n  |location=Johannesburg\n  |year=1959\n  |oclc=36230980\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Deur sonskyn en skaduwee\n  |trans-title=Through Sunshine and Shadow\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher=Dagbreek-Boekkring\n  |location=Johannesburg\n  |year=1961\n  |oclc=504531563\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title=Die maatstok\n  |trans-title=The Dipstick\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |oclc=14643120\n  |publisher=Dagbreek-Boekkring\n  |location=Johannesburg\n  |year=1963\n}}\n\n=== Nonfiction ===\n* {{cite book\n  |title = The Bronze Killer: The Story of a Family's Fight Against a Very Common Enemy - Hemochromatosis\n  |first=Marie|last=Warder\n  |publisher = Imperani Publishers Publishers\n  |year=1989\n  |isbn=0-88925-885-6\n}} (Updated in 2000 as ''The Bronze Killer: New Edition'' (Dromedaris Books, {{ISBN|9780968735800}}) including \"Iron: The Other Side of the Story\", a layman's guide to hemochromatosis)\n\n== Recognition ==\n{{multiple image|align=right\n|image1=Ottawa1991.jpg|width1=215|caption1=Warder with the Canada Volunteer Medal of Honour\n|image2=|width2=138|caption2=Warder's Medal of Honour\n}}\n\nFor her efforts in founding the CHS, Warder was presented with a certificate of appreciation on 11 April 1988 by Mayor G.J. Blair, of Richmond, British Columbia \"in recognition of her contribution to voluntary service\" in that city, one year after he had been the first Mayor in Canada to proclaim an annual week of awareness for Hemochromatosis. During the first Awareness Week, 523 new cases of hemochromatosis were diagnosed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdnhemochromatosis.ca/about/history.php |title=History |publisher=Canadian Hemochromatosis Society |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706172308/http://www.cdnhemochromatosis.ca/about/history.php |archivedate=6 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she was presented with a Lifetime Achievement Award at the International Bio-Iron Conference held in Vancouver, \"honoring her lifelong involvement and dedication to the awareness of Hemochromatosis around the world.\"<ref>{{cite news\n |url          = http://www.delta-optimist.com/health/Lifetime+award+author/4886690/story.html\n |title        = Lifetime award for author\n |work         = The Delta Optimist\n |date         = 3 June 2011\n |author       = Staff\n |access-date  = 3 June 2011\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110826052836/http://www.delta-optimist.com/health/Lifetime+award+author/4886690/story.html#\n |archive-date = 26 August 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref>   Some years ago, the Minister of Health for Canada declared May each year to be a month of National Awareness for the disorder and it is now also observed by organizations in other countries for instance the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/ahc-asc/minist/messages/_2009/2009_05_26-eng.php |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706182051/http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/ahc-asc/minist/messages/_2009/2009_05_26-eng.php |archivedate=6 July 2011 |title=Message from Leona Aglukkaq, Minister of Health: Hemochromatosis Month \u2013 May 2009 |accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref><ref>http://www.hemochromatosiscny.org/</ref>{{Relevance inline|date=November 2012}}\n\nWarder was awarded the Canada Volunteer Award in 1991 by the [[Health and Welfare Canada]] for her work and advocacy of raising awareness of hemochromatosis.<ref name=\"Selection 1995\">\n{{cite journal\n | title       = La tueuse au masque du bronze\n | journal     = Selection\n | location    = Quebec\n | date        = November 1995\n |trans-title=The Bronze Killer\n}}</ref><ref>Anderson, Donna. \"Hard-working volunteers honored with national award\". ''The Vancouver Sun'' [Vancouver, B.C] 5 July 1991: C8. Quote: \" Bea Leinback, Marie Warder and Joanna Tudan-Sainberg were among 25 people across the country who received this year's Canada Volunteer Award during a ceremony in Ottawa last week. And in keeping with the selfless character of the volunteer, they say their biggest joy was the national recognition their organizations were accorded. The award was established by Health and Welfare Canada to acknowledge the efforts of volunteers to improve the health and social well-being of their fellow Canadians.\"</ref><ref>''Delta Optimist'' (June 1991)</ref>{{Ref|***|***}}\n\n== Death ==\nWarder died on 20 October 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marie Warder Obituary|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/vancouversun/obituary.aspx?pid=173174075|accessdate=8 June 2015|publisher=Vancouver Sun|date=15 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Note|*|*}}''Storm Water'' and ''Samaritaan van die Sahara'' in [[Afrikaans language|Afrikaans]] and ''Penny of the Morning Star'' in English. The last was commissioned for use by [[English as a second language|ESL]] students, and thus contained an English/Afrikaans glossary as well as comprehension questions. An updated version for general reading, without the English/Afrikaans glossary and comprehension questions, was issued in time for Christmas 2010.<ref name=DeltaOptimistNov2010/>\n\n{{Note|**|**}}''Hart Sonder Liefde'' and ''Penny of the Morning Star - the story of a girl reporter''\n\n{{Note|***|***}}Text of Certificate: \"Through Marie Warder\u2019s research and most noted book, ''The Bronze Killer'', she has educated doctors and the general public about the disorder. As a result, hemochromatosis is now recognized as Canada\u2019s most common genetic disorder, and routine blood tests for the disorder may soon become standard diagnostic procedure.\"\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Warder, Marie}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ficksburg]]\n[[Category:South African non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:South African women novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toTsawwassen(link changed toTsawwassen, British Columbia) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marie_Warder"}
{"title_page": "Bugzy Malone", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Bugsy Malone}}\n{{copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Bugzy Malone\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Aaron Davis\n| alias            = {{hlist|Bugzy Malone|Bugz}}\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1990|12|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Manchester]], England\n| origin           = Manchester, England\n| genre            = [[Grime (music)|Grime]], [[British hip hop]]\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Rapper|songwriter}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 2010\u2013present\n| label            = Ill Gotten Records<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6649409/little-mix-chemical-brothers-uk-charts|title=Little Mix Score Their Longest-Running No. 1 on U.K. Charts With 'Black Magic'|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n| associated_acts  = [[Chip (rapper)|Chip]], [[Stormzy]], [[Tinie Tempah]], [[Charlie Sloth]]\n| website          = {{URL|thebugzymaloneshow.co.uk/}}\n}}\n\n'''Aaron Davis'''<ref name=\"PL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.publishedlive.com/2016/05/01/manchester-mc-bugzy-malone-facing-time-in-prison/|title=BREAKING: Manchester MC Bugzy Malone Facing time in prison|date=1 May 2016|accessdate=21 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220210237/http://www.publishedlive.com/2016/05/01/manchester-mc-bugzy-malone-facing-time-in-prison/|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> (born 20 December, 1990), better known by his stage name '''Bugzy Malone''', is a British rapper and actor, from Manchester, England.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mobo.com/news-blogs/new-ep-bugzy-malone-walk-me|title=New EP: Bugzy Malone 'Walk With Me' - MOBO Awards|work=mobo.com|accessdate=17 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003093249/http://www.mobo.com/news-blogs/new-ep-bugzy-malone-walk-me|archive-date=3 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Malone has been described as one of the key artists instigating a \"grime revival\" moving the UK urban scene away from more commercially oriented music<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/jul/24/this-weeks-new-live-music|title=Bugzy Malone, Colleen Green, Archie Shepp: this week\u2019s new live music|author=John Robinson|work=the Guardian|accessdate=17 August 2015}}</ref> and the first artist  in the [[Grime (music genre)|grime]] genre from Manchester to have commercial success in the UK.<ref name=\"Noisey\">{{Cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/8xaxp4/how-bugzy-malone-became-grimes-king-of-the-north|title=How Bugzy Malone Became Grime's King of the North|website=Noisey|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref>\n\nBugzy's album ''King of the North'' was released on 14 July, 2017 and peaked at {{Abbr|No.|Number}} 4.\n\n== Early life ==\nAaron Davis was born on 20 December, 1990 in [[Crumpsall|Crumpsall, Manchester]].<ref name=\"MEN\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/bugzy-malone-manchester-interview-12055376|title=Bugzy Malone - putting Manchester on the map for all the right reasons|last=Quinn|first=Seamus|date=2016-10-20|work=Manchester Evening NEws|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Being born in a family of \"career criminals\", Davis grew up in a poverty-stricken household, not meeting his father during his youth<ref>{{Citation|last=Wireless Festival|title=Wireless TV {{!}} Bugzy Malone interview {{!}} 2017|date=2017-07-27|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K5H4bBHliBc|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref> and seeing his step father as his role-model until his parents were eventually divorced due to a case of [[Domestic violence|domestic abuse]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/j5pe77/bugzy-malone-king-of-the-north-interview|title=track-by-track: bugzy malone puts manchester on the map with king of the north|website=I-d|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Davis grew up being influenced by his family members who he says had a criminal \"reputation\"<ref name=\"MEN\" /> with numerous family members being involved in criminal activities, including his uncle who Davis witnessed being shot in the face with a shotgun.<ref name=\"Standard\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/music/bugzy-malone-interview-a3286206.html|title=Bugzy Malone: The way I am is built into me \u2013 I didn't get an option|work=Evening Standard|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Davis first began involving himself with criminal activities when he was eleven years old and was eventually expelled from secondary school in [[Year Nine|year nine]] when he was fourteen.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> After being expelled, Davis continued a life of criminal behavior until he was arrested and sent to [[HM Prison Stoke Heath|HMP Stoke Heath]] at sixteen,<ref name=\"Boakye\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jul/27/grime-mc-bugzy-malone-when-youre-from-outside-london-youd-better-be-special|title=Grime MC Bugzy Malone: 'When you're from outside London, you'd better be special'|last=Boakye|first=Jeffrey|date=2017-07-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-09-12|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> missing his [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] exams.<ref name=\"Inrerview\">{{cite web|title=Bugzy Malone #AskBugzyMalone Interview [MIXTAPE OUT SOON]|date=2014-01-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1GBdx144CIo|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref>\n\nAfter leaving prison at seventeen, Davis took up the sport of boxing as a hobby in an attempt to find a career<ref name=\"Boxing\">{{cite web|title=The Bugzy Malone Show - Episode 1 'King of the North'|date=2017-07-24|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9RDM2y5ZFOc|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref> but also to distract himself from the urge to dip back into the life of criminality.<ref name=\"Standard\" /> Davis still practices boxing as a hobby.<ref name=\"Boxing\" /> During his time taking boxing as a career, Davis moved close to his biological father in [[Marple, Greater Manchester]] before the two eventually lost contact. Davis then moved close to [[Heaton Park]] when he was twenty.<ref name=\"Noisey\" />\n\nDavis was inspired to start rapping from the influential \"''Risky Roadz''\" DVD series that also inspired the careers of [[Dizzee Rascal]], [[Wiley (rapper)|Wiley]] and [[Skepta]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-radar/bugzy-malone-interviewed-im-trying-to-create-art-out-of-the-pain-that-i-ve-experienced-15232|title=Bugzy Malone Interviewed: 'I'm Trying To Create Art Out Of The Pain That I\u2019ve Experienced' - NME|date=2015-09-28|work=NME|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Davis began rapping with his friends when they would often congregate or commit crimes.<ref name=\"Standard\" /> His friends would play instrumentals from their mobile phones which Davis would then [[Freestyle rap|freestyle]] on.<ref name=\"BBC Radio 1Xtra\">{{Citation|last=BBC Radio 1Xtra|title=Charlie Sloth's Rap Up - 24 Jul - Bugzy Malone & Dr. Vades|date=2015-08-25|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5AvZpZcGR6o|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref> Davis received the nickname \"Bugz\" whilst in a gang when he was 13 years old and it later developed into \"Bugzy Malone\" when he was serving his prison sentence. After leaving prison, Davis began to take music seriously as a side hobby to his then-growing boxing career.<ref name=\"BBC Radio 1Xtra\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== 2010\u20132015: Career beginnings ===\nDavis released his debut mixtape, titled ''SwaggaMan'' in 2010. He began doing freestyles for northern grime YouTube channel KODH TV<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCchd-iN6RAYqzfr_w1UPEcA|title=KODH TV|website=YouTube|access-date=2016-11-30}}</ref> on their series ''Spray Out Freestyle''.<ref>{{cite web|author=KODH TV|title=Bugzy Malone - KODH TV|date=2010-11-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gp1kTl1cQtc|accessdate=2016-11-30}}</ref> He then did freestyles on popular urban [[YouTube]] channels including [[GRM Daily|Grime Daily]]. In 2011, Davis released his second mixtape ''Why So Serious,'' inspired by ''[[The Dark Knight Rises|Batman: The Dark Knight Rises]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebugzymaloneshow.co.uk/why-so-serious/|title=Why So Serious {{!}} The Bugzy Malone Show.co.uk|website=The Bugzy Malone Show.co.uk|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> The lead single from the mixtape ''\"Hip Hop Heavy Metal\"'' was released on 21 September, 2011 and the music video currently has 1.3 million views on YouTube.<ref>{{Citation|last=Bugzy Malone|title=BUGZY MALONE ~ HIP HOP HEAVY METAL (OFFICIAL VIDEO)|date=2011-09-12|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HJiAxKtS284|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref> ''Lost in Meanwhile City'', Davis' third mixtape was released in 2012. Writing about the mixtape on his website, Davis said <blockquote>I called this mixtape \"Lost In Meanwhile City\" because I stumbled across a film called '[[Franklyn]]' \u2014 I felt like I could relate to the dark atmosphere at the time and also some of the featured characters faced similar problems I felt I was faced with i.e family problems, girl problems, law suits, depression. I felt 'Lost In Meanwhile City' was the perfect metaphor for my position in life at that particular time, I felt lost and basically in a world of my own.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebugzymaloneshow.co.uk/lost-in-meanwhile-city/|title=Lost In Meanwhile City {{!}} The Bugzy Malone Show.co.uk|website=The Bugzy Malone Show.co.uk|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> </blockquote>The lead single for the project and the second music video created by Davis was released on 23 August, 2012.<ref>{{Citation|last=Bugzy Malone|title=Bugzy Malone ~ Nightmares (OFFICIAL VIDEO)|date=2012-08-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yg5oZicsbxk|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref> In 2014, Davis announced his fourth mixtape, ''Journal of an Evil Genius'' and begun a \"mixtape campaign\" where he'd release music videos with narratives that would coincide with the singles released from the mixtape, alike a \"visual album\".<ref name=\"RM\">{{Cite news|url=http://respect-mag.com/2014/02/interview-bugzy-malone-a-voice-from-the-underground/|title=Interview: Bugzy Malone, A Voice From The Underground {{!}} RESPECT.|date=2014-02-14|work=RESPECT.|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> The visuals were released in the form of a YouTube video every Monday at 19:00 for six weeks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wjlondon.com/interview-5-bugzy-malone/|title=Interview: A quickie with... Bugzy Malone -|date=2014-02-18|work=WJ London Lifestyle|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Speaking about the idea to do a campaign consisting of videos to promote the mixtape, Davis listed [[Quentin Tarantino]] as an influence and said \"I felt as if I wanted to tell a story loosely based on reality and used the raw emotion of the songs as an excuse to create a mini-horror movie.\"<ref name=\"RM\" /> As of 2017, the videos have 5M+ views combined on YouTube.<ref>{{Citation|last=Bugzy Malone|title=Bugzy Malone ~ Rainmaker [OFFICIAL MUSIC VIDEO]|date=2014-02-17|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OrUKe99-akk|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Bugzy Malone|title=Bugzy Malone - San Andreas Mentality [OFFICIAL VIDEO]|date=2014-06-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A2Po3gtrXUc|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Bugzy Malone|title=Bugzy Malone ~ Childhood Memories [OFFICIAL MUSIC VIDEO]|date=2014-02-10|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=awuOd6JHVRc|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Bugzy Malone|title=Bugzy Malone ~ Troubled & Tormented [OFFICIAL MUSIC VIDEO]|date=2014-02-24|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwQvH6bGC5Y|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Bugzy Malone|title=Bugzy Malone ~ Evil Genius [OFFICIAL MUSIC VIDEO]|date=2014-03-03|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lBVaCE0KjEY|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Bugzy Malone|title=Bugzy Malone ~ Unwelcome Guest [OFFICIAL MUSIC VIDEO]|date=2014-02-03|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HShT4ELRN6Y|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref> The mixtape was released on 10 February, 2014. Talking about the mixtape, Davis wrote on his website <blockquote>I called this mixtape 'The Journal of an Evil Genius' mainly because that is what it is. The songs themselves are written in a journal-like style making this record the one that means the most to me. The \"Evil Genius\" is an alias I came up with one day in the studio and it just kind of stuck. This project is an Intricate/accurate story about my past all the way back to childhood going right the way up to the present giving it a journal-like feel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebugzymaloneshow.co.uk/the-journal-of-an-evil-genius/|title=The Journal Of An Evil Genius {{!}} The Bugzy Malone Show.co.uk|website=The Bugzy Malone Show.co.uk|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== 2015\u2013present: Feud with Chip, ''Walk with Me'', ''Facing Time'' and ''King of the North'' ===\nOn 7 September, 2014 Davis released a 'Spitfire' freestyle on JDZmedia which went on to get his first million views on YouTube. This gave him more popularity outside Manchester and later earned him a performance on ''Fire in the Booth'' with [[Charlie Sloth]] on [[BBC Radio 1Xtra]]. Davis released his latest ''Fire in The Booth'' on 14 March, 2015.<ref name=\"noisey\">{{cite web|url = https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/which-mc-recorded-the-best-ever-fire-in-the-booth | first = Paul | last = Gibbins | date = 1 March 2016 | accessdate = 22 October 2016 | work = Noisey | publisher = [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] | title = Which MC Recorded the Greatest 'Fire in the Booth'?}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LPXoDDs1OM8|title=Fire In The Booth \u2013 Bugzy Malone|date=14 March 2015|work=YouTube|accessdate=17 August 2015}}</ref> When Davis originally received a phone call from Sloth requesting an appearanced on Radio 1Xtra's ''Fire in the Booth'' segment, he thought it was a [[prank call]].<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/mar/09/why-doesnt-everyone-rap-in-scouse-how-british-hip-hop-broke-free-of-london|title=Why doesn't everyone rap in scouse? How British hip-hop broke free of London|last=MacInnes|first=Paul|date=2017-03-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-09-12|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Bugzy Malone's ''Fire in the Booth'' is currently the most viewed video in the series with eleven million views.<ref>{{Citation|last=BBC Radio 1Xtra|title=Fire In The Booth \u2013 Bugzy Malone|date=2015-03-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LPXoDDs1OM8|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref> In May 2016, 1Xtra released Davis' second ''Fire in the Booth'' which currently has six million views.<ref>{{Citation|last=BBC Radio 1Xtra|title=Fire in the Booth \u2013 Bugzy Malone Part 2|date=2016-05-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DbrXNrXEho8|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref> During his ''Fire in The Booth'', Davis dissed fellow grime artist [[Chip (rapper)|Chip]]. Chip, two days later, published a tweet on the social media platform, Twitter saying \"The name you can ride off... CHIPMUNK!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/OfficialChip/status/577561862025441281|title=The name you can ride off... CHIPMUNK!|date=16 March 2015|website=@OfficialChip|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> before replying to his critics including Davis lyrically on the song \"Pepper Riddim\" which was released on 20 March, 2015.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yDHXvyk4yK0|title=CHIP - PEPPER RIDDIM (NET VIDEO)|date=20 March 2015|work=YouTube|accessdate=17 August 2015}}</ref> This started a grime feud and drew attention to the [[Grime (music)|grime scene]].<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YYqKNglQhpI|title=Bugzy Malone - Relegation Riddim [@TheBugzyMalone] - Link Up TV|date=25 March 2015|work=YouTube|accessdate=17 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.complex.com/music/2015/03/the-best-british-rap-verses-of-the-month-war-edition-march/bugzy-malone-relegation-riddim|title=2. Bugzy Malone \u2013 \"Relegation Riddim\" - The Best British Rap Verses Of The Month (War Edition) - Complex UK|author=Tobi Oke|work=Complex UK|accessdate=17 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004103648/http://uk.complex.com/music/2015/03/the-best-british-rap-verses-of-the-month-war-edition-march/bugzy-malone-relegation-riddim|archive-date=4 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bespokemag.co.uk/bugzy-malone-fires-back-at-chip-with-relegation-riddim/|title=Bugzy Malone fires back at Chip with \u2018Relegation Riddim\u2019|author=Sidney Korboe|work=BESPOKE MAGAZINE|accessdate=17 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007010412/http://bespokemag.co.uk/bugzy-malone-fires-back-at-chip-with-relegation-riddim/|archive-date=7 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Several days later on 25 March, Davis released \"Relegation Riddim\". The music video on YouTube featured numerous artists who were included in the feud, including [[Big Narstie]]. The video currently has 12M+ plus views making it Davis' most viewed music video.<ref>{{Citation|last=Link Up TV {{!}} Music|title=Bugzy Malone - Relegation Riddim [@TheBugzyMalone] {{!}} Link Up TV|date=2015-03-25|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YYqKNglQhpI|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref> On 3 April, 2017 Chip released \"The End\" which Davis replied to with \"The Revival.\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Chiptubeofficial|title=CHIP - THE END|date=2015-04-03|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PytuDUIIjxU|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Link Up TV {{!}} Music|title=Bugzy Malone - The Revival {{!}} @TheBugzyMalone {{!}} Link Up TV|date=2015-04-07|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4D9hmcVC--s|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref> Five months later in September, Chip replied to \"The Revival\" with six tracks which led to Davis replying twice. This would be the last time Davis replied to Chip who later went on to include two more diss tracks before stopping.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://grimebeef.com/bugzy-malone-vs-chip/|title=Bugzy Malone vs Chip - Grime Beef|date=2015-10-22|work=Grime Beef|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> In July 2017, Davis released a documentary-style vlog in promotion for his EP ''King of the North'' where he directly references the feud, saying <blockquote>He phoned me saying 'Yo listen, we can do this thing like a, back and forth ting and shine some light on your career'\" but you know yourself, I've been grinding at this point for six years. I don't need anybody to shine. Right, so, it was a case of \"alright, cool\" and it was quite a civilized conversation. He was like \"we can do festivals together\" and this that and the other and I was like \"yeah, I hear that bro, but I kind of already wrote my response.\"<ref name=\"Noisey\"/></blockquote>On 13 June, 2015 on BBC Radio 1, DJ MistaJam premiered Malone's first official single \"Watch Your Mouth\" and the video was released on Malone's YouTube channel the same night. The track went on to be played across UK radio and popular TV networks, including Capital Xtra, Bang Radio, Kiss 100, Reprezent, Unity Radio, BBC Xtra, Radio 1, Asian Network, Westside FM, MTV Base, Flava TV, Kiss TV and Channel AKA. On 24 July, 2015, Malone released his first EP ''[[Walk with Me (Bugzy Malone EP)|Walk with Me]]'', which entered at number 8 on the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-chemical-brothers-heading-for-sixth-number-1-album-with-born-in-the-echoes__10160/|title=The Chemical Brothers heading for sixth Number 1 album|work=officialcharts.com|accessdate=17 August 2015}}</ref> Davis also set up his own record label, titled \"Ill Gotten Records\" in an attempt to assist Manchester based artists.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.brightersound.com/just-announced-bugzy-malone/|title=Just Announced: Bugzy Malone - Brighter Sound|date=2016-07-06|work=Brighter Sound|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref>\n\nDavis released ''Facing Time'', his second EP, which went to number 6 on the UK Albums Chart on 16 June, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/facing-time/|title=facing-time {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> In promotion of the EP, Davis released a trilogy of visuals titled \"Section 8(1)\" meant to coincide with the subject matter of the EP. On 27 August, released the first \"chapter\" with the same name as his hit song, \"Beauty and the Beast\". On 28 August, 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TheBugzyMalone/status/769687649116364800|title=Bugzy Malone on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref> chapter 2 was released and this time based on the song \"Facing Time\". On 29 August, 2016, the third and final chapter was released, this time on the song \"I Suggest\". \"Section 8(1)\" is produced by G. Kuba and Davis himself. In promotion of the EP, Davis also planned a publicity stunt about himself being arrested in an armed robbery.<ref name=\"PL\" />\n\nDavis released his first charting single on 18 May, 2017 \"Through The Night\" with [[DJ Luck & MC Neat]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Bugzy Malone|title=Bugzy Malone - Through The Night (Feat. DJ Luck and MC Neat)|date=2017-05-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uRNoLOHiUo0|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref> The song charted at 92, making it Davis' first charting single on the [[UK Singles Chart|UK singles chart]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/51751/bugzy-malone-dj-luck-mc-neat/|title=BUGZY MALONE/DJ LUCK/MC NEAT {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Davis released his third EP ''King of the North'' on 14 July, 2017.<ref>{{Citation|title=King of the North by Bugzy Malone on Apple Music|date=2017-07-14|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/king-of-the-north/id1236113373|accessdate=2017-09-12}}</ref> The album charted at 4 on the UK Album Charts<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/king-of-the-north/|title=king-of-the-north {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> and had three charting singles, \"Through the Night\", \"Memory Lane\" and \"Bruce Wayne\", charting at 92, 74 and 99 respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/47916/bugzy-malone/|title=BUGZY MALONE {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Davis was announced as one of the artists performing at the [[Manchester Arena|Manchester Evening News Arena]] reopening<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/we-are-manchester-arena-concert-13597755|title=How the #WeAreManchester gig perfectly summed up the Manc spirit|last=Bourne|first=Dianne|date=2017-09-10|work=men|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> and posted on his personal Twitter account following his performance \"I've told them before and i'll tell them again Manchester is the home of the brave...\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TheBugzyMalone/status/907344284847833090|title=I've told them before and i'll tell them again Manchester is the home of the brave... pic.twitter.com/U2jwEMvxex|last=Malone|first=Bugzy|date=11 September 2017|website=@TheBugzyMalone|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref>\n\nA photo of Davis and Chip pictured together at Giggs' birthday party was uploaded to Instagram on 13 December, 2017. This led to speculation that their two year long feud was either over or had been faked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/42338966/chip-and-bugzy-malone-pictured-together-after-years-of-beef|title=Chip and Bugzy Malone pictured together after years of beef - BBC Newsbeat|date=2017-12-13|website=BBC Newsbeat|access-date=2017-12-16}}</ref> Davis explained the photo, stating that he reconciled with Chip and ended their feud at the party.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ol9WSPBbbSE</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\n\n=== Musical style ===\nDavis lists his biggest inspiration as [[Tupac Shakur]].<ref name=\"MTV\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/bugzy-malone/news/get-to-know-bugzy-malone-introducing-interview|title=Get to Know: Bugzy Malone {{!}} MTV UK|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> The ''Guardian'' has called Davis a trendsetter for Manchester's urban music scene, mainly its grime scene where he was the first Manchester grime artist to reach national commercial success.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/aug/14/mc-bugzy-and-the-manchester-grime-scene|title=How MC Bugzy Malone put Manchester on the grime map|last=Considine|first=Clare|date=2015-08-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-09-12|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> When asked to describe his sound by MTV, Davis called his sound an \"Evolution of Grime.\"<ref name=\"MTV\" /> Davis' mancunian accent is a trademark of his vocal style<ref name=\"Guardian\" /> which has been described as \"deep-from-the-diaphragm\".<ref name=\"TAD\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartsdesk.com/new-music/cd-bugzy-malone-facing-time|title=CD: Bugzy Malone - Facing Time {{!}} The Arts Desk|website=www.theartsdesk.com|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref>\n\nDavis has been praised for his writing style which has been called \"introspective\",<ref name=\"TAD\" /> \"confessional\",<ref name=\"Review\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/nov/13/bugzy-malone-review-grime-royal-albert-hall-manchester|title=Bugzy Malone review \u2013 northern grime star bares his soul in tales of the city|last=Simpson|first=Dave|date=2016-11-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-09-12|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and \"unique\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/parklife-festival-2016-bugzy-malone-achieves-impossible-facing-time-ep-enters-uk-charts-1565217|title=Bugzy Malone's Facing Time EP enters UK charts|last=Adejobi|first=Alicia|date=2016-06-14|work=International Business Times UK|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Davis' lyrics usually deal with criminality, poverty and emotional suffering.<ref name=\"Review\" /> Davis' delivery has been called \"clear, powerful and precise\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rainbowexoticmusic.com/bugzy-malone-king-of-the-north-album-review/|title=Bugzy Malone: \"King of The North\" Album Review \u22c6 Rainbow Exotic Music|date=2017-07-16|work=Rainbow Exotic Music|access-date=2017-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913065447/https://www.rainbowexoticmusic.com/bugzy-malone-king-of-the-north-album-review/|archive-date=13 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and fast-rapid when he is rapping.<ref name=\"Review\" />\n\n=== Fashion ===\nIn May 2016, Davis started a partnership with Supply & Demand for a fashion line that would mainly encompass [[Tracksuit|track suits]]. The line began being sold at retail chain [[JD Sports]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kingsmediatv.com/2016/05/29/bugzy-malone-joins-forces-supply-demand-new-clothing-range/|title=Bugzy Malone Joins Forces With Supply & Demand In New Clothing Range|date=2016-05-29|work=KINGSMEDIA|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> and has so far dropped three sets of the Supply & Demand collaboration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/JDSportsOfficial/photos/a.394754729716.172917.108909479716/10155542656004717/?type=3|title=JD Sports|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Davis' clothing is mainly merchandise that has been formatted into high-end fashion wear. The clothing generally has traits of things that Davis likes, such as the superhero, Batman.<ref name=\"Boakye\"/>\n\n== Legal issues ==\nDue to his upbringing, Davis has had several legal issues arise. When Davis was sixteen, he was arrested and sent to [[HM Prison Stoke Heath|HMP Stoke Heath]].<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> In January 2015, Davis assaulted a man outside of the Panacea nightclub in alleged self defense.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/panacea-attack-cctv-witness-appeal-8700782|title=Police issue CCTV images of four people after man violently attacked outside Manchester nightspot Panacea|last=Bainbridge|first=Pete|date=2015-02-23|work=Manchester Evening News|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nOn March 26, 2020, Davis was seriously injured after being involved in a motorcycle crash in Bury. Footage circulated on [[Twitter]] of the rapper riding his motorcycle, followed by videos of him lying on the floor in the aftermath of the collision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/26/bugzy-malone-suffers-horrific-motorcycle-crash-taken-away-stretcher-12457874/|title=Bugzy Malone 'involved in serious motorcycle accident'|last=Griffin|first=Louise|date=2020-03-26|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:17em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Certifications\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;font-size:90%;\" | [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br /><ref name=\"UK\">Peaks in the United Kingdom:\n* For all except where noted: {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/47916/bugzy-malone|title=Bugzy Malone {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=22 July 2017}}\n* For \"Through the Night\": {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/51751/bugzy-malone-dj-luck-mc-neat/|title=Bugzy Malone/DJ Luck/MC Neat {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=22 July 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Irish Albums Chart|IRL]]<br>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[B. Inspired]]''\n|\n* Released: 17 August 2018\n* Format: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 6 || 19\n|\n* [[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]: Silver<ref name=\"BPI\"/>\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of extended plays, with selected chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:17em;\"| Extended play details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Certifications\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;font-size:90%;\" | [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br /><ref name=\"UK\"/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;font-size:90%;\" | [[UK R&B Chart|UK<br />R&B]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Walk with Me (Bugzy Malone EP)|Walk with Me]]''\n|\n* Released: 24 July 2015\n* Format: CD, digital download\n| 8 || 2\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Facing Time''\n|\n* Released: 3 June 2016\n* Format: CD, digital download\n| 6 || \u2014\n|\n* BPI: Silver<ref name=\"BPI\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[King of the North (EP)|King of the North]]''\n|\n* Released: 14 July 2017\n* Format: CD, digital download\n| 4 || \u2014\n|\n* BPI: Silver<ref name=\"BPI\"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"font-size:90%\" | \"\u2014\" denotes a recording that did not chart or was not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n===Mixtapes===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of non-commercial mixtapes\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:11em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:17em;\"| Album details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''SwaggaMan''\n|\n* Released: 2010\n* Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Why So Serious''\n|\n* Released: 2011\n* Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Lost in MeanWhile City''\n|\n* Released: 2012\n* Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''The Journal of an Evil Genius''\n|\n* Released: 2014\n* Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Stereotyped''\n|\n* Released: January 2015\n* Format: Digital download\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n====As lead artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! colspan=\"3\" | Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;font-size:90%;\" | [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br /><ref name=\"UK\" />\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;font-size:90%;\" | [[UK Independent Singles Chart|UK<br/>Ind.]]<br /><ref name=\"UKindie\">Peak positions on the UK Indie Chart:\n* All except where noted: {{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/independent-singles-chart/20160610/130/|title=Official Independent Singles Chart Top 50 - 10 June 2016 - 16 June 2016|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Irish Singles Chart|IRE]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Relegation Riddim\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/relegation-riddim-single/980599768|title=Relegation Riddim - Single by Bugzy Malone|work=[[iTunes Store]] (UK)|accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2015\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"4\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Zombie Riddim\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/zombie-riddim-single/1052776151|title=Zombie Riddim - Single by Bugzy Malone|work=iTunes 